h3. Issue Summary
When we copy a link from a header and paste this link into another Confluence page, clicking on this link using /MS EdgeIE11 doesn't place us to the linked heading.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Open IE11/MSE Edge;
# Create a page *Test A*;
# Insert some content along with the page;
# Add a header 1 in the bottom of the page;
# Publish *Test A*;
# Copy the link from the header;
# Create a page *Test B*;
# Insert paste the header link;
# Publish *Test B*;
# Click over the link.

h3. Expected Results
You are redirected to the header in *Test A*.

h3. Actual Results
You fall at the top of the page, as a regular link does.

h3. Workaround
Use a different browser, like Chrome or Mozilla Firefox.

h3. Issue Summary
For the new *Linkable Headings* feature, when the headings contain a special character that is changed to unicode in the heading link, that link won't always work.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page;
# Add a heading 1 with text "_Heading..._";
# The three dots will be converted to *%E2%80%A6*, in unicode on the hading link;
# Publish the page;
# Copy the heading link and edit the page;
# Insert [some text|https://www.lipsum.com/feed/html] in the page and then hyperlink the last word, pasting the heather link;
# Insert more text and repeat the same hyperlinking step;
# Publish the page;
# Click in the first hyperlinked text - it will take some seconds to work;
# Click in the second hyperlink (or in the same one again).

h3. Expected Results
You are brought to the header.

h3. Actual Results
The hyperlink won't bring you to the header.

h3. Workaround
Remove the special characters from the heading, so you can use its link as the expected.

h3. Summary

When we are working with JIRA and Confluence while trying to create a JIRA issue using the JIRA macro within a draft page, in case JIRA doesn't have any project, it will retrieve a message to us with: "_You do not have permission to create issues on this JIRA server._"

!image-2020-02-18-11-53-13-996.png|width=467,height=326!
h3. Steps to reproduce
 # Have a JIRA and Confluence site;
 # Make sure your JIRA site doesn't have any project yet;
 # Go to a Confluence page and edit it (don't forget to have JIRA and Confluence linked each other);
 # Call the *JIRA macro*;
 # In the macro modal, choose *Create New Issue*.

h3. Suggestion

Instead of misleading the user with a messaging informing there are no permissions on JIRA, inform that there is no JIRA project created on that site, providing a *_Create a Project_* link with the message.

h3. Issue Summary
When using the *Linakable Headings* feature in Confluence to link them within the same page they are placed, the hyperlinked text won't work well if it has formatting in it (like *bold*, _italic_ or +underlined+).

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page;
# In the first line, add any heading style;
# Insert some content in the page, letting it being scrollable in the view mode;
# In the last line of the text, add a random word and publish the page;
# Go to the heading you inserted and copy its link;
# Edit the page;
# Scroll down to the last random word you inserted and add the header link into with *CTRL + K* / *COMMAND + K*;
# Format this word to be *B*, _I_ or +U+;
# Publish the page;
# Click over the link.

h3. Expected Results
It places you to the respective heading.

h3. Actual Results
It places you 3 or 4 lines after the heading, letting the Confluence topbar over the heading.

h3. Workaround
Avoid highlighting hyperlinks using these formats for the moment.

h3. Issue Summary
We have a cool option in Confluence that allows us to nest *Page Properties Report* macros within *Page Properties* to get the reference in other pages with *Page Properties Report*. Though, the last page with *Page Properties Report* won't work if the *Page Properties Report* from the page before is set to *Current Space* - it is a bit complex to get it, but following the below steps let things clearer, I promise.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
*Creating the source page*:
# Create a page called *Page-1*;
# Insert the *Page Properties* macro and fill it with a simple table with any content;
# Add a label called *Page 1* on this page.

*Creating the first report*:
# In the same space, create a new page called *Page 2*;
# Insert the *Page Properties* macro;
# Within this macro, insert the *Page Properties Report* macro;
# In the label field, add *Page-1*;
# In the space field, set *Current space*;
# Publish the page;
# Insert a label *page-2*.

*Getting the issue*
# On any different space, create a new page called *Page 3*;
# Insert the *Page Properties Report* macro;
# In the label field, set it as *page-2*;
# Publish the page.

h3. Expected Results
The nested information is shown in the page.

h3. Actual Results
The nested info stays as *No content found.*

*NOTES*:
* It is possible to see the content in the macro preview on *Page 3*;
* It happens that, in *Page 3*, the nested macro inherits the settings from the macros in *Page 2*, so Confluence gets lost.

h3. Workaround
On *Page 2*, remove the space information (_current space_) from the *Page Properties Report* macro and the info will be shown in *Page 3*.

As of today, when you create an indented numbered list, it continues with letters instead of numbers, as follows:
{code:java}
1. Item one; 
2. Item two; 
    a. Item two.one;
    b. Item two.two; 
3. Item three; 
{code}
This suggestion is in order to have this behavior changed so the numbered list continues only with numbers, like this one:
 # Item one
 # Item two
 ## Item two.one
 ## Item two.two

In [this documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/confcloud/confluence-wiki-markup-938044804.html], we can see the following statement:
{quote}
In numbered lists as described above, the format of the 'number' displayed at each list level may be different, depending upon your browser and the style sheets installed on your Confluence site. So in some cases, you may see letters (A, B, C, etc; or a, b, c, etc) or Roman numerals (i, ii, iii, etc) at different list levels.
{quote}

However, we believe that there should be a way for Confluence to force the use of only numbers.
